<sn><md>### Study

&gt; **Geology** is the `study of Earth and its structure`, including rocks. <br>
&gt; **Petrology** focuses on the `origin and nature of rocks` <br>
&gt; While **Mineralogy** `examines the minerals` that form them.

These studies have deepened understanding of Earth’s history, human development, and technological progress.

The scientific study of rocks became formalized in the `19th century` with the rise of **Plutonism**. The discovery of `radioactive decay` in 1896 enabled `radiometric dating`, and the `plate tectonics theory` in the 20th century further advanced geological science.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Classification

Rocks are `mainly made up of mineral grains`—++crystalline solids++ formed by atoms arranged in an orderly pattern. Some rocks also contain `mineraloids`, such as volcanic glass, which ++lack a crystalline structure++. The types and amounts of minerals in a rock depend on how the rock was formed.

Most rocks are rich in `silicate minerals`, which make up about `95% of Earth’s crust`. The **silica content** of a rock largely determines its `properties and classification`.

Rocks are categorized by features like **mineral and chemical composition**, **texture**, **permeability**, and **particle size**, all of which reflect their formation process. Through the **rock cycle**, rocks can change from one type to another, forming the three main classes: **igneous**, **sedimentary**, and **metamorphic**.

These classes have many subgroups, but their boundaries are gradual rather than distinct—rocks often blend into one another as mineral proportions and structures vary continuously.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Igneous Rock

:::.row
:::.col-12 .col-md-6
**Igneous rocks** (from the Latin *igneus*, meaning “of fire”) form when `magma or lava cools and solidifies`. Magma originates from partial melting of pre-existing rocks in the **mantle or crust**, usually due to increased temperature, decreased pressure, or compositional changes.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![igneous-rock-image](https://image-v2.cdn.app.senecalearning.com/2018-08/67b01384-1a52-440e-ac1e-48d85833ffd4/igneous-rock-magma-molten-lava-,h_400,q_80,w_640.jpg)
:::
:::


There are two main types of igneous rocks:

* **Plutonic (intrusive) rocks** – form when `magma cools slowly beneath the Earth’s surface`, e.g., **granite**.
* **Volcanic (extrusive) rocks** – form when `lava or ejecta cools on the surface`, e.g., **basalt** or **pumice**.

As magma rises, it undergoes **magma differentiation**, becoming `richer in silica`—the key factor in classifying igneous rocks, followed by alkali oxide content.

Igneous rocks make up about **65% of Earth’s crust**:

* **66%** basalt and gabbro
* **16%** granite
* **17%** granodiorite and diorite
* **0.6%** syenite
* **0.3%** ultramafic rocks

The `oceanic crust` is almost entirely ++basalt++,<br> while ++granite and granitoids++ dominate the `continental crust`.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Sedimentary Rock

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
**Sedimentary rocks** form at the Earth’s surface through the `accumulation, compaction, and cementation` of fragments of pre-existing rocks, minerals, or organic matter, or by chemical precipitation from water. This process, called **sedimentation**
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![sedimentary-rock-image](https://t4.ftcdn.net/jpg/08/83/71/33/360_F_883713332_PduhHLKCqld0zhPGJAMiQvpla7rG1wbP.jpg)
:::

:::


**Sediments** originate from the `weathering and erosion` of earlier rocks and are **transported** by agents such as **water, wind, ice, or gravity** before settling in layers. These layers, known as `strata`, give sedimentary rocks their typically horizontal, **stratified** appearance and often contain **fossils**.

By volume, sedimentary rocks make up about `7.9%` of Earth’s crust, consisting of:

* **82% shale**
* **12% sandstone and arkose**
* **6% limestone**

Sediments are also classified by **grain size**:
**clay → silt → sand → gravel**, with larger particles like **cobbles** and **boulders** in some systems.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Metamorphic Rock

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
**Metamorphic rocks** form when existing rocks—igneous, sedimentary, or older metamorphic—are `exposed to high temperatures and pressures` different from their original formation conditions, a process known as **metamorphism** (“change in form”). This causes `recrystallization` of minerals, altering the rock’s structure and composition. Metamorphism typically occurs at `temperatures above 150–200°C` and `pressures above 1500 bars`, such as during **continental plate collisions**. Metamorphic rocks make up about `27.4%` of Earth’s crust.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-md-6
![metamorphic-rock-image](https://cdn.zmescience.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/slate_warp_west_coast_portugal-736525-1024x768.jpg)
:::

:::


The main types of metamorphism are:

* **Contact metamorphism** – caused by heat from nearby magma.
* **Pressure (burial) metamorphism** – caused by deep burial under sediment.
* **Regional metamorphism** – caused by both heat and pressure, often in mountain-building zones.

Based on texture, metamorphic rocks are classified as:

* **Foliated** – with `layered or banded` structures (e.g., **schist**, **gneiss**, **slate**, **phyllite**, **mylonite**).
* **Non-foliated** – `without distinct layering` (e.g., **marble**, **quartzite**, **soapstone**, **serpentine**, **hornfels**).
